      <scopecontent id="aspace_8c7f5260bdb11be98dc3e06b31f5212c">
         <head>Content Description</head>
         <p>The collection documents the life and career of Robert Bradford Williams, African American lawyer and graduate of Yale College, 1885, who settled in New Zealand.  Materials include a copy and transcription of Williams' diary from his trip to Australia and New Zealand in 1887; published articles about Williams; and correspondence between the donor, Kent A. Leslie and Williams' granddaughter, Jane Paul.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_bd3cb56da92a271c24e589fd82ed052a">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>
      </accessrestrict>
      <bioghist id="aspace_6a4e8361e6953d31f752c29e6609fcd2">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Robert Bradford Williams was born on June 24, 1860 in Augusta, Georgia. He attended school at the Williston Academy in Massachusetts, and later attend Yale University, where he graduated in 1885. After he graduated from Yale Williams joined the Fisk Jubilee Singers, the choir of Fisk University, and embarked on a world tour with the singers. He married Katherine Josephine Burke while in Australia; in 1890 the two settled in Wellington, New Zealand. In New Zealand, Williams became a lawyer, forming a partnership with Vincent Meredith and founding the law firm Meredith Connell. Williams also entered politics and in 1902 became the mayor of the Wellington borough of Onslow, serving for five years. Williams died on May 28, 1942 in Otaki Beach, New Zealand.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <arrangement id="aspace_b196b0a48abb5172dc6685b114c35c0b">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The collection is arranged in three groupings: Robert Bradford Williams 1887 diary, Jane Paul files, and Kent A. Leslie files.</p>
      </arrangement>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_69b2b75cf7ef1f6e236d9b0115099da0">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>Gift of Kent A. Leslie, 2019.</p>
      </acqinfo>
      <prefercite id="aspace_a4183a413b619ee7fc0ce44e4292c7a6">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
